    "summary": "LangChain and LlamaIndex are two prominent frameworks for building AI applications with large language models (LLMs), particularly for implementing retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) systems. LangChain is characterized as a versatile, modular platform supporting numerous use cases, while LlamaIndex focuses more specifically on indexing and information retrieval from text-based sources. Both frameworks aim to enhance LLM capabilities by providing domain-specific knowledge and improving the accuracy of AI applications. LangChain is noted for its flexibility in building a wide range of natural language processing (NLP) and agentic AI applications, while LlamaIndex is often described as ideal for simpler workflows and straightforward AI applications. The development of these frameworks, along with others in the multi-agent AI system (MAS) space, has been rapid and has shaped how LLM applications are developed and orchestrated. A large-scale study of open-source MAS, including LangChain and similar frameworks, revealed varying development profiles and common issues faced in their evolution and maintenance.",

